entry.name: uddisub_missingwsdl
entry.text: Update for service/port {%1$s}%2$s/%3$s with key %4$s references an unknown WSDL file (%5$s).
entry.description: In some mappings from WSDL to UDDI, the description of a service port (a UDDI bindingTemplate) is separated from the description of the service interface, which is captured in a tModel. Because a given subscription only covers one kind of UDDI component (business,service,bindingTemplate,or tModel) updates for these components are received independently. This message indicates that an update was received for a bindingTemplate component (service port), referencing a tModel component (wsdl interface) about which the system has not yet received any information. This message may indicate that the subscription for the tModels is not properly formulated, or that no such subscription exists, or it may simply indicate that the notifications were received in the reverse order. In the latter case, the situation will be resolved when the tModel update is processed.
entry.suggestion: To check if the situation was resolved by further updates, check the current status of the subscribed service ports in the UDDI Subscription Service Status panel. The status of service ports which reference an unknown WSDL file will be listed as MissingWSDL. If only some services have MissingWSDL, then the tModel subscription may be too narrow for the corresponding service or bindingTemplate subscription. If all or many of the services in a specific subscription object have MissingWSDL, a tModel subscription may not have been registered with either the registry or the router's subscription object, or it may have expired. Alternately, errors may have occurred in processing the tModel notifications.

entry.name: ws_proxy_published_component_conflict
entry.text: Possible conflict publishing the WS-Proxy effective WSDL for port %1$d and URL %2$s: duplicate %3$s components named %4$s.
entry.description: A potential conflict was encountered while attempting to publish the effective WSDL for a Web Service Proxy. The effective WSDL is a description of the services available to clients on the frontside of the Web Service Proxy on a specific URL and port. The effective WSDL for a Web Service Proxy on a given port and URL is generated with all of the WSDL files that have services attached to the given URL and port. If multiple WSDL files are combined that contain conflicting definitions for the same messages, ports, bindings, or services, only one copy of each definition is published. This message has no effect on the behavior of the Web Service Proxy, which are its registered operations or the implied validation or other policy applied to them), but might result in an incoherent or incomplete effective WSDL.
entry.suggestion: Ensure that the services for the Web Service Proxy are associated with distinct ports, URLS, or both ports and URLs. To protect against conflicts when WSDL files are combined within the same port and URL, ensure that each WSDL file (and each imported or included WSDL or schema file) uses a distinct target namespace. When not possible, ensure that each WSDL and schema document defines distinctly named components.
